Use `||` (or) between checks so the whole condition is `true` if any single one is `true`. For example, this runs when someone is hungry, thirsty, or both:

```javascript
if (isHungry() || isThirsty()) {
  rest()
}
```

Use `&&` (and) so both sides must be `true`. For example, this only runs when someone is hungry AND thirsty:

```javascript
if (isHungry() && isThirsty()) {
  drink()
}
```

Either way is enough on its own, so you have two options.

The first is to write a separate `if` for each way, both doing the same action:

```javascript
if (isHungry() && hasSnack()) {
  eat()
}
if (isThirsty() && hasSnack()) {
  eat()
}
```

The second is to combine both ways into a single `if` with `||`, wrapping each way's checks in brackets so the `&&` parts group together before the `||` splits them:

```javascript
if ((isHungry() && hasSnack()) || (isThirsty() && hasSnack())) {
  eat()
}
```

Work out each way's requirements on its own first, then use whichever style you find clearer.
